  '<h2 id="threat-catalog">Threat catalog <a class="anchor" href="#threat-catalog">#</a></h2>',
  '<ul>',
  '<li><strong>Shape malformation</strong> — input is not RFC 3339 / ISO 8601 datetime. The regex requires <code>YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS</code> with optional fractional seconds and optional offset.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Year window</strong> — year before <code>minYear</code> (default 1970) or after <code>maxYear</code> (default 9999) often indicates a parsing bug or sentinel-leak shape.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Naive datetime</strong> (no offset) — strict refuses; downstream interpretation depends on local timezone, breaks cross-region equality.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Non-UTC offset</strong> — strict accepts only <code>Z</code> / <code>+00:00</code>; balanced accepts any offset; permissive allows naive too.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Leap-second `60`</strong> — RFC 3339 §5.6 explicitly valid (<code>23:59:60Z</code> is a real wall-clock time); most parsers panic. Strict refuses; balanced audits; permissive allows.</li>',
  '<li><strong>Excessive fractional precision</strong> — RFC 3339 allows any digits after the dot but every consuming system has a cap; flags > <code>maxFractionalDigits</code> (default 9, nanosecond precision).</li>',
